cks-all-military-recruitment-heads-over-frontline-bribes-scandal-ukraine" target="_blank">Zelenskiy sacks military recruitment heads over frontline bribes scandal</a></h2><div class="description"> Ukrainian president describes taking of cash from people who want to avoid conscription as form of treachery. Volodymyr Zelenskiy has announced the dismissal of all the heads of Ukraine’s regional military recruitment centres. Officials were accused of taking bribes from those seeking to avoid the frontlines.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 19:08:18 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/11/zelenskiy-sacks-all-military-recruitment-heads-over-frontline-bribes-scandal-ukraine" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/12/its-a-brilliant-atmosphere-flags-fans-and-fun-as-englands-women-win" target="_blank">‘It’s a brilliant atmosphere’: flags, fans and fun as England’s women win</a></h2><div class="description"> England beat Columbia 2-1 in the World Cup quarter-final at south London’s Boxpark Croydon. The result puts England in the semi-finals for the first time in their history. England are now bidding to win their first ever World Cup in Brazil.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 17:46:16 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/12/its-a-brilliant-atmosphere-flags-fans-and-fun-as-englands-women-win" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/13/another-interest-rate-rise-news-on-prices-and-wages-may-decide" target="_blank">Another interest rate rise? News on prices and wages may decide</a></h2><div class="description"> Financial markets are betting that there is a 80% chance of a 0.25 percentage-point rise, to 5.5%. The MPC will look closely at this week’s earnings and inflation figures. Energy volatility could also come into play as the MPC meets on 21 September.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 23:05:30 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/13/another-interest-rate-rise-news-on-prices-and-wages-may-decide" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/12/never-again-is-britain-finally-ready-to-return-to-the-office" target="_blank">‘Never again’: is Britain finally ready to return to the office?</a></h2><div class="description"> Amazon has issued a warning to staff who are not spending at least three days a week in the office. Meta wants its workers to do the same from next month. Zoom, whose revenues jumped 300% during the first year of the pandemic, last week asked employees to come in for at least two days a. week.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 15:15:21 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/12/never-again-is-britain-finally-ready-to-return-to-the-office" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/13/in-pursuit-of-repetitive-beats-vr-acmi-melbourne-international-film-festival" target="_blank">‘The night is literally in my hands’: what it’s like to attend an acid house rave – in virtual reality</a></h2><div class="description"> In Pursuit of Repetitive Beats tracks the acid-house movement and rave scene in Coventry, UK. Using VR and haptic vests to transport users to a sweaty club in 1980s Britain, the film is so realistic that you might need a lie down afterwards.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 20:00:27 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/13/in-pursuit-of-repetitive-beats-vr-acmi-melbourne-international-film-festival" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2023/aug/12/cerys-bradley-not-overthinking-things-2019-review-laughing-horse-bar-50-edinburgh" target="_blank">Cerys Bradley: Not Overthinking Things 2019 review – divorce, autism and pass the parcel</a></h2><div class="description"> Cerys Bradley throws a kids’ birthday bash full of nostalgic fun as they discuss their parents’ recent split. Bradley deftly immerses the audience in games and stories. The show is packed with fun distractions - pass the parcel, pin the tail on the donkey, balloon modelling – yet Bradley can’t help but overthink.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 19:00:25 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2023/aug/12/cerys-bradley-not-overthinking-things-2019-review-laughing-horse-bar-50-edinburgh" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/12/lee-anderson-conservative-brutally-honest-or-just-nasty" target="_blank">Lee Anderson: a brutally honest politician – or just another nasty Tory?</a></h2><div class="description"> Conservative party deputy chairman Lee Anderson was interviewed by Nigel Farage on Farage’s GB News show last week. He had told the Daily Express that if asylum seekers didn’t want to stay on the Bibby Stockholm barge in Portland harbour, they could “f*** off back to France”</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 13:59:08 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/12/lee-anderson-conservative-brutally-honest-or-just-nasty" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/12/this-is-how-we-do-it-i-initiate-sex-99-per-cent-of-the-time-but-im-ok-with-that" target="_blank">This is how we do it: ‘I initiate sex 99.9% of the time, but I’m OK with that’</a></h2><div class="description"> Alison and Sam make a game of planning their lovemaking hours in advance. He'll ask and she'll often say no, at first. He reads my body language so perfectly. If she's comfortable not having an orgasm, that should be fine, but it’s still a challenge for me.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 11:00:16 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/12/this-is-how-we-do-it-i-initiate-sex-99-per-cent-of-the-time-but-im-ok-with-that" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/12/putting-down-roots-in-denmark-a-remarkable-renovation" target="_blank">Putting down roots in Denmark: a remarkable renovation</a></h2><div class="description"> Carla Cammilla Hjort's Danish farm has been restored by her globetrotting owner. The Re:Arc Institute is a non-profit initiative that works at the intersection of architecture and climate action. She founded Copenhagen’s Trailerpark Festival before becoming the part-owner and chairwoman of Space10, Ikea's global innovation lab.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 15:02:20 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/12/putting-down-roots-in-denmark-a-remarkable-renovation" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2023/aug/12/england-colombia-womens-world-cup-not-how-champions-play-but-win" target="_blank">England’s brutish triumph is not how champions play. But it is how champions win | Jonathan Liew</a></h2><div class="description"> The Lionesses have been made to fight before, but scarcely in a game of this magnitude and intensity. The England substitutes in their tracksuits bound on to the pitch in blissful release. Niamh Charles has a smile the width of Sydney Harbour, Jordan Nobbs wheels her arms around like a DJ.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 15:30:21 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2023/aug/12/england-colombia-womens-world-cup-not-how-champions-play-but-win" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2023/aug/13/history-making-matildas-stand-up-on-near-perfect-evening-of-high-drama" target="_blank">History-making Matildas stand up on near-perfect evening of high drama | Jack Snape</a></h2><div class="description"> Matildas winger Hayley Raso played 104 minutes in quarter-final win over France. Raso was substituted after being substituted for penalty shootout win. Australia beat France 7-6 on penalties in World Cup quarter-finals at the World Cup in Brisbane. Australia are now bidding for a fourth straight World Cup title in Brazil.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 14:37:23 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2023/aug/13/history-making-matildas-stand-up-on-near-perfect-evening-of-high-drama" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2023/jul/20/womens-world-cup-2023-golden-boot-top-goalscorers-game-by-game" target="_blank">Women’s World Cup 2023 Golden Boot: top goalscorers, game by game</a></h2><div class="description"> Golden Boot is awarded to the player who scores most goals in the tournament. Ties are settled by assists, then by minutes per goal. Own goals do not count, nor do penalties scored in shootouts, but penalties in normal or extra time do. Australia’s Sam Kerr is one of the favourites to win the award.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 07:26:57 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2023/jul/20/womens-world-cup-2023-golden-boot-top-goalscorers-game-by-game" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/12/england-wales-rugby-world-cup-warmup-report" target="_blank">George Ford leads England to victory against Wales but Owen Farrell sees red</a></h2><div class="description"> Owen Farrell was shown yellow for a shoulder to the head of Wales replacement Taine Basham. The fly-half was shown a red card for the tackle in the 19-17 win over Wales. Owen Farrell could be without captain for England's opening World Cup opener against Argentina.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 18:52:58 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/12/england-wales-rugby-world-cup-warmup-report" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><